    <subfield code="a">According to Medvedev and Scanlon [14] , a polynomial <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∈</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math> of degree <math altimg="si133.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>d</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>2</mn></math> is called disintegrated if it is not conjugate to <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></msup></math> or to <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo>±</mo><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> (where <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></msub></math> is the Chebyshev polynomial of degree d ). Let <math altimg="si6.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>n</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant="double-struck">N</mi></math> , let <math altimg="si34.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>∈</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math> be disintegrated polynomials of degrees at least 2, and let <math altimg="si742.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>φ</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>×</mo><mo>⋯</mo><mo>×</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math> be the corresponding coordinate-wise self-map of <math altimg="si75.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> . Let X be an irreducible subvariety of <math altimg="si75.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> of dimension r defined over <math altimg="si10.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover></math> . We define the φ-anomalous locus of X which is related to the φ-periodic subvarieties of <math altimg="si75.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> . We prove that the φ -anomalous locus of X is Zariski closed; this is a dynamical analogue of a theorem of Bombieri, Masser, and Zannier [4] . We also prove that the points in the intersection of X with the union of all irreducible φ -periodic subvarieties of <math altimg="si75.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> of codimension r have bounded height outside the φ -anomalous locus of X ; this is a dynamical analogue of Habegger's theorem [8] which was previously conjectured in [4] . The slightly more general self-maps <math altimg="si742.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>φ</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>×</mo><mo>⋯</mo><mo>×</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math> where each <math altimg="si11.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub><mo>∈</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> is a disintegrated rational function are also treated at the end of the paper.</subfield>
